elementMetadata.description:
Square has a separate API endpoint for testing against Sandbox accounts. Instead of `connect.squareup.com`, the endpoint is `connect.squareupsandbox.com`. As the Cloud Elements Square Element was built to authenticate and make requests to the former, this Element will allow users to authorize requests against the latter. You can visit this web page: https://developer.squareup.com/docs/oauth-api/walkthrough to see an example of the OAuth at work.

Users must have their own Square Application with an authorized Sandbox Test Account. Visit the Square developer dashboard to create an Application, Sandbox Test Account, create OAuth tokens, and grant your application specific permissions to your sandbox seller account(s). Visit this link to do so: https://squareup.com/login?app=developer&return_to=https://developer.squareup.com/apps

Users must also have the Sandbox Account open in the browser before attempting to authenticate, or Square will send back an error telling users to do so before authenticating through Cloud Elements.
elementMetadata.name: SquareSandbox

configuration.description: SquareSandbox This helps find all instances pertaining to an incoming event. The EVENT_NOTIFICATION_INSTANCE_FINDER is composed of two values, in the form "[INSTANCE_CONFIG_PROPERTY_KEY]|[JSON_PATH_TO_PROPERTY_VALUE]". The first value, INSTANCE_CONFIG_PROPERTY_KEY, is the element config key that we will use to determine which instances this event pertains to.  The second value, JSON_PATH_TO_PROPERTY_VALUE, is the JSON XPath to the event JSON that we will use to lookup the instances.  For example, GitHub sends the organization name back in their response, and we save this element config value as "github.organization", so the instance finder for GitHub would be "github.organization|organization.login"
configuration.name: Event Notification Instance Finder
